'''Alexander Mikhaylovich Butlerov''' (Алекса́ндр Миха́йлович Бу́тлеров; 15 September 1828 &ndash; 17 August 1886) was a [[Russian Empire|Russian]] [[chemist]], one of the principal creators of the theory of [[chemical structure]] (1857&ndash;1861), the first to incorporate [[double bond]]s into structural formulas, the discoverer of [[hexamine]] (1859), the discoverer of [[formaldehyde]] (1859) and the discoverer of the [[formose reaction]] (1861).
He first proposed the idea of possible tetrahedral arrangement of valence bonds in carbon compounds in 1862.
The crater [[Butlerov (crater)|Butlerov]] on the [[Moon]] is named after him.
Alexander Butlerov was born in [[Chistopol]] into a landowning family.
