{{Taxobox | name = Malayan water shrew<ref name=msw3>{{MSW3 Hutterer | pages = 275}}</ref> | status = NT | trend = unknown | image = | image_width = 250px | status_system = IUCN3.1 | status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{Cite journal | author = Chiozza, F. | title = ''Chimarrogale hantu'' | journal = [[The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species]] | volume = 2008 | page = e.T4647A11058654 | publisher = [[IUCN]] | date = 2008 | url = http://oldredlist.iucnredlist.org/details/4647/0 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2008.RLTS.T4647A11058654.en | access-date = 15 January 2018}}</ref> | regnum = [[Animal]]ia | phylum = [[Chordata]] | classis = [[Mammal]]ia | ordo = [[Eulipotyphla]] | familia = [[Soricidae]] | genus = ''[[Chimarrogale]]'' | species = '''''C. hantu''''' | binomial = ''Chimarrogale hantu'' | binomial_authority = [[John Leonard Harrison|Harrison]], 1958 | range_map = Malayan Water Shrew area.png | range_map_caption = Malayan water shrew range }}
The '''Malayan water shrew''' (''Chimarrogale hantu''), also known as the '''hantu water shrew''', is a [[red-toothed shrew]] recorded only from the [[Malaysia]]n state of [[Selangor]]. It was listed as a critically endangered, but is now considered near threatened.<ref name=iucn/>
It gets its scientific name ''hantu'' from the [[Malay language|Malay]] word for [[ghost]].
==Anatomy== The Malayan water shrew has a white underside, a black coat along its top and sides and a fringe of bristles running along the surface of the tail and on the paws which act as swimming aids. The teeth have red tips. The Malayan water shrew can grow up to about 10&nbsp;cm in height and 20&nbsp;cm in length.
==Habitat== The Malayan water shrew lives in the [[Tropical Rainforests]] of [[Peninsula Malaysia]]. It lives mainly by fresh water lakes and rivers surrounded by vegetation and spends much of its time underwater. Underwater this shrew likes to stay in leafy areas to avoid predators and surprise its prey, which include fish, frogs and plants.
